  "prompt": "What is the work profile of Scientist/Engineer - Power Electronics at ISRO (for example at SAC-Ahmedabad)?",
  "response": "At ISRO (Indian Space Research Organisation), specifically at the Space Applications Centre (SAC) in Ahmedabad, a Scientist/Engineer in Power Electronics typically has the following work profile:\n\nKey Responsibilities:\n1. Design and development of power electronics systems for space applications\n2. Creating power conversion and conditioning circuits\n3. Designing power supply units for spacecraft and satellites\n4. Developing high-reliability power management systems\n5. Conducting thermal and reliability analysis of electronic systems\n6. Designing power electronics for solar panels and battery management\n7. Developing embedded control systems\n8. Performing simulation and modeling of power electronic circuits\n\nTechnical Skills Required:\n- Advanced knowledge of power electronics\n- Expertise in analog and digital circuit design\n- Proficiency in MATLAB/Simulink\n- Circuit simulation tools\n- Embedded systems programming\n- Thermal management techniques\n- Understanding of spacecraft power requirements\n\nTypical Qualifications:\n- M.Tech/M.E. in Electronics/Electrical Engineering\n- Strong background in power electronics\n- Research experience\n- Knowledge of space technology fundamentals\n\nWork Environment:\n- Advanced research laboratory\n- Collaborative team-based projects\n- High-precision technical work\n- Emphasis on innovation and reliability\n\nThe role demands technical excellence, innovation, and commitment to space technology development.",
